         ( <i>cheering</i> )           

02:06.176 --> 02:09.411
( <i>indistinct sportscast on TV</i> ) 

02:09.446 --> 02:12.347
        ( <i>dings loudly</i> )        

02:12.382 --> 02:14.349
REBECCA:                        
Attention, everyone, attention! 

02:14.384 --> 02:16.586
I'm getting rid                 
of that television.             

02:16.620 --> 02:18.287
         ( <i>groaning</i> )           

02:18.321 --> 02:20.355
And I am replacing it           
this weekend                    

02:20.390 --> 02:22.124
with a new 27-inch screen TV    

02:22.158 --> 02:25.160
with a direct hookup            
to the Cable Sports Channel.    

02:25.195 --> 02:26.261
    Thank you.                  

02:26.296 --> 02:27.964
 ( <i>applause and cheering</i> )      

02:27.998 --> 02:29.799
Kind of a jerky thing to do,    

02:29.833 --> 02:31.366
but I liked it.                 

02:31.401 --> 02:33.102
                 NORM:          
                 That means     
                 we'll be able  

02:33.136 --> 02:35.337
to watch that world welterweight
championship bout               

02:35.371 --> 02:36.956
between Hector                  
"The Hammer" Rodriguez          

02:36.991 --> 02:38.424
and Julio                       
"The Hacker" Rodriguez.         

02:38.459 --> 02:39.258
Who do you think's gonna win?   

02:39.293 --> 02:40.943
My money's on Rodriguez.        

02:41.879 --> 02:43.078
 Julio "The Hacker" Rodriguez   

02:43.113 --> 02:44.246
     has got a glass jaw.       

02:44.281 --> 02:46.582
My uncle Fergie had a glass eye.

02:46.617 --> 02:49.552
He used to take it out          
and scare the cat.              

02:52.589 --> 02:55.090
    This is Cheers, Dorothy.    

02:55.125 --> 02:57.860
     Isn't it amusing?          

02:57.895 --> 03:00.129
 Frasier, would you be a dear   
    and get us some drinks?     

03:04.401 --> 03:05.668
        Sam, can I have         

03:05.702 --> 03:06.719
         three martinis please? 

03:06.753 --> 03:07.787
             Make mine a double.

03:07.821 --> 03:08.988
    How's married life          
    treating ya?                

03:09.022 --> 03:10.089
    Quite a change, huh?        

03:10.123 --> 03:11.456
                 Well, you know,
                 Lilith and I   

03:11.491 --> 03:13.625
         did live together for  
         a year before we wed.  

03:13.660 --> 03:15.761
         So other than the fact 
         that I now see it      

03:15.796 --> 03:17.429
            stretching          
            endlessly before me,

03:17.463 --> 03:19.231
             until I lie rotting
             in the grave,      

03:19.265 --> 03:20.733
     there's no real difference.

03:20.767 --> 03:22.885
Now, Lilith, if you,            
your family,                    

03:22.919 --> 03:25.804
and generations of your         
ancestors had lived             

03:25.806 --> 03:28.591
with the boot of oppression     
on your throat,                 

03:28.625 --> 03:31.910
would cutting out a man's heart 
seem that extreme?              

03:31.945 --> 03:35.481
            So who's            
            the party girl?     

03:35.515 --> 03:36.749
             Dorothy Greenberg. 

03:36.783 --> 03:39.918
     She's an old childhood chum
     of Lilith's from New York. 

03:39.953 --> 03:41.820
            She's been          
            visiting for a week.

03:41.855 --> 03:43.088
         She's a                
         professional student.  

03:43.123 --> 03:44.923
                She's writing   
                her dissertation

03:44.958 --> 03:48.361
            on the Comuneros'   
            uprising in Paraguay
            during the 1700s.   

03:48.395 --> 03:50.496
            She can't talk      
            about anything else.

03:50.530 --> 03:53.432
         Believe me, when       
         you've heard one       
         Bruno de Zavala joke,  

03:53.467 --> 03:54.667
         you've heard them all. 

03:58.739 --> 04:00.072
Sam, I got to                   

04:00.106 --> 04:02.074
get this over with.             

04:02.108 --> 04:04.277
Listen, there's something       
I got to ask you,               

04:04.311 --> 04:06.512
and I don't want you            
to take it the wrong way.       

04:06.546 --> 04:07.513
                     What is it?

04:07.547 --> 04:10.033
Would you come to dinner        
at my house tonight?            

04:10.067 --> 04:12.101
                Hey, I thought  
                we were friends.

04:12.136 --> 04:13.269
Well, it's just that            

04:13.303 --> 04:15.304
Eddie wants us                  
to practice our social skills   

04:15.338 --> 04:17.238
so he can invite                
his boss over to dinner.        

04:17.274 --> 04:18.507
                 Can't you ask  
                 somebody else? 

04:18.541 --> 04:19.676
                Please? Come on.

04:19.709 --> 04:20.976
                I'm sure any one
                of the guys     

04:21.011 --> 04:22.545
would love to go.               

04:22.579 --> 04:24.246
                 Guys, am I...  

04:26.550 --> 04:29.401
So, uh...                       
I'll expect you at 7:00?        

04:29.435 --> 04:30.970
                Yeah, all right.
                All right.      

04:34.674 --> 04:36.492
     Where'd you guys go?       

04:36.526 --> 04:37.793
    Go?                         
                        Huh?    

04:37.828 --> 04:40.396
We were right here              
all the time, Sammy.            

04:40.430 --> 04:42.097
                 By the way, uh,

04:42.131 --> 04:44.299
             thanks for hogging 
             that invitation    

04:44.334 --> 04:46.568
             to Carla's house   
             all for yourself.  

04:46.603 --> 04:48.337
                 There's room   
                 for one more.  

04:55.428 --> 04:57.613
             Sam, you sit here. 

04:57.648 --> 04:59.415
                Thank you.      

04:59.449 --> 05:01.183
 What is this, Sammy-- no date? 

05:01.217 --> 05:02.852
         Uh, your mom didn't    
         want me to bring one.  

05:02.886 --> 05:03.853
                 I always like  

05:03.887 --> 05:04.954
to be the prettiest woman       

05:04.988 --> 05:06.022
in my house.                    
                    ( <i>chuckles</i> )

05:06.056 --> 05:07.790
 And you always will be, baby.  

05:07.824 --> 05:10.225
    You're no magazine cover    
         yourself.              

05:14.515 --> 05:16.215
             Now.               

05:24.658 --> 05:27.460
EDDIE:                          
Oh, these look great.           

05:27.494 --> 05:28.661
    Mm-hmm.                     

05:45.312 --> 05:46.345
                You know, Carla,

05:46.380 --> 05:48.047
     it's, uh, nice to see you  

05:48.081 --> 05:50.349
         surrounded by          
         such a loving family.  

05:50.384 --> 05:53.386
Oh, it's eerie, Sam.            
                     Mmm.       

05:53.420 --> 05:54.487
I got a husband                 

05:54.521 --> 05:55.821
             who does windows.  

05:55.855 --> 05:57.990
And all the kids                
are out of jail.                

06:00.194 --> 06:02.195
For the first time in my life,  

06:02.229 --> 06:04.063
when morning comes around,      

06:04.097 --> 06:07.132
I want to open up my eyes       
instead of my wrists.           

06:07.167 --> 06:09.068
    That's beautiful, honey.    

06:11.071 --> 06:12.271
Uh, and who knows, Ma?          

06:12.306 --> 06:14.307
Someday... well,                
you can look forward            

06:14.341 --> 06:15.741
to having grandkids.            

06:15.775 --> 06:17.910
         ( <i>laughing</i> ):          
         Carla, a grandmother?  

06:17.944 --> 06:19.545
     You've got to be kidding.  

06:19.580 --> 06:21.647
No, no.                         

06:21.682 --> 06:23.148
Sammy, it's true.               

06:23.183 --> 06:25.651
         I think I'd like to be 
         a grandmother someday. 

06:25.686 --> 06:26.785
I mean, get all the fun,        

06:26.820 --> 06:28.087
none of the responsibility.     

06:28.121 --> 06:30.189
Just seeing the little brats    
when I want to.                 

06:30.224 --> 06:31.990
I think you're gonna            
be surprised                    

06:32.025 --> 06:34.159
what a sweet                    
little old granny I'll be.      

06:34.194 --> 06:36.662
That's great,                   
'cause I knocked up Annie good. 

06:36.697 --> 06:37.396
What!?                          

06:39.433 --> 06:40.466
    Hey, hey, hey!              

06:40.500 --> 06:42.602
    Oh! Oh! Carla!              

06:42.636 --> 06:45.271
Carla! Carla!                   

06:45.305 --> 06:47.340
 What are you thinking of?!     

06:47.374 --> 06:49.342
    I just waxed that table.    

06:49.376 --> 06:51.210
         Come here, come here.  
         Come on, come on.      

06:51.245 --> 06:52.878
             Get off. Come on.  

06:52.912 --> 06:54.714
         Come here, come here.  

07:00.820 --> 07:02.555
    And besides...              

07:02.589 --> 07:04.423
        this is family business.

07:04.458 --> 07:06.058
Let's, um...                    

07:07.060 --> 07:09.194
         Let's talk             
    about this later, okay?     

07:09.228 --> 07:11.363
                     ( <i>sighs</i> )  

07:26.079 --> 07:28.814
So what kind of car             
do you drive, Ed?               

07:30.750 --> 07:31.984
I thought you said              

07:32.018 --> 07:33.719
you wanted to be a grandmother. 

07:33.753 --> 07:35.120
                        Someday.

07:35.154 --> 07:36.188
            Like years from now,

07:36.222 --> 07:38.724
        when you've moved       
        thousands of miles away.

07:38.759 --> 07:40.493
         Carla, please.         

07:44.798 --> 07:47.232
I drive a Corvette myself.      

07:48.435 --> 07:49.902
         How could you do this?!

07:49.936 --> 07:52.805
             Hey, I'm going to  
             be 20 in two years.

07:52.839 --> 07:56.041
                 I can hear my  
                 biological     
                 clock ticking. 

07:56.075 --> 07:58.744
         Do you know what it    
         takes to raise a kid?  

07:58.778 --> 08:00.613
Ma, will you relax?             
I got a job.                    

08:00.647 --> 08:02.181
             You think you can  
             support a family   

08:02.215 --> 08:03.315
         pushing cheeseburgers?!

08:03.350 --> 08:04.950
Well, I thought                 
we'd all stay here.             

08:04.984 --> 08:06.285
                 Ho-ho, great.  

08:06.319 --> 08:08.120
                 More people    
                 in this house. 

08:08.155 --> 08:10.656
                 I get about 19 
                 on the highway,
                 15 in town.    

08:12.292 --> 08:15.927
     Whose stupid idea          
     was this anyway?           

08:15.962 --> 08:18.564
     Hey, I was getting bored   
     sitting around the house.  

08:18.598 --> 08:20.999
I thought this might            
give her something to do.       

08:21.034 --> 08:22.000
         I'll give you          

08:22.035 --> 08:23.202
something to do!                

08:24.237 --> 08:25.771
            Oh!                 
                        EDDIE:  
                        No, no. 

08:25.805 --> 08:27.739
    Carla, Carla, Carla!        

08:27.774 --> 08:30.376
            Come on.            

08:30.410 --> 08:31.644
                         Well...

08:31.678 --> 08:34.111
     if this is the way         
that we are going to be treated 

08:34.147 --> 08:36.048
     on the happiest day        
     of our young lives,        

08:36.082 --> 08:38.484
     then I don't want          
 to live in this house anymore! 

08:40.520 --> 08:41.886
                Anthony!        

08:41.921 --> 08:43.556
     You should probably        
         come with me.          

08:43.590 --> 08:46.842
    But we haven't eaten yet.   

08:46.876 --> 08:48.577
     Your hair is full          
     of bread crumbs.           

08:48.611 --> 08:51.046
 We could butter your head      
     and make a sandwich.       

08:52.382 --> 08:55.250
I had a sandwich for lunch!     

08:55.285 --> 08:56.518
Oh, go on.                      
Go, go!                         

08:56.552 --> 08:57.519
Get out of here!                

08:57.553 --> 08:58.988
Let's see how long              
you last on your own!           

08:59.022 --> 09:00.555
I give you three days!          

09:00.590 --> 09:02.658
Two, two tops! You hear me?     

09:02.692 --> 09:05.161
                Carla, come on. 
                Calm down.      

09:06.696 --> 09:11.466
 Sammy, you get 15 in the city? 

09:11.501 --> 09:13.919
             Hey, so they're    
             gonna have a baby. 

09:13.953 --> 09:15.171
They'll, they'll find their way 
         through it.            

09:16.206 --> 09:19.408
     You don't understand.      

09:19.442 --> 09:20.642
        My life is over.        

09:20.677 --> 09:23.045
 I'm going to be a grandmother. 

09:23.079 --> 09:24.163
I mean,                         

09:24.314 --> 09:26.131
 I might as well wrap myself up 

09:26.165 --> 09:27.466
     in a black babushka,       

09:27.500 --> 09:30.001
     get fat and grow hairs     
        out of my moles.        

09:30.036 --> 09:31.503
                    Oh, come on.

09:31.538 --> 09:32.771
                     ( <i>laughs</i> ) 

09:32.805 --> 09:34.005
                 You're         
                 exaggerating.  

09:34.040 --> 09:36.542
         Do I have              
 to get out the family album?   

09:36.576 --> 09:38.093
CARLA:                          
Oh, God,                        

09:38.128 --> 09:39.628
     this is terrible.          

09:40.830 --> 09:42.998
        Look at my life.        

09:43.033 --> 09:44.299
    I never had a childhood.    

09:44.333 --> 09:46.468
 I married Nick when I was 15.  

09:46.502 --> 09:49.155
Never got to go                 
to the prom or homecoming,      

09:49.189 --> 09:50.956
     to a slumber party,        

09:50.990 --> 09:53.792
     to Fort Lauderdale         
        on Spring Break.        

09:53.826 --> 09:56.061
     Or on one lousy date       
         with Fabian.           

09:57.947 --> 09:59.999
     Now I don't even get       
         a middle age.          

10:00.033 --> 10:03.301
 Go straight from grade school  
         to Granny.             

10:03.336 --> 10:04.486
 I don't know what to say,      

10:04.521 --> 10:05.604
                         Carla. 

10:05.638 --> 10:07.173
 Just don't say anything, okay? 

10:07.207 --> 10:08.490
There's nothing                 
anybody can say                 

10:08.524 --> 10:09.808
 that's gonna change anything,  

10:09.842 --> 10:11.210
 so just don't say anything.    

10:11.244 --> 10:11.677
     Yeah, but, Carla...        

10:11.711 --> 10:13.028
Sam, I said don't say anything. 

10:13.062 --> 10:14.363
 Weren't you listening to me?   

10:14.397 --> 10:14.914
         Yes, Carla...          

10:14.948 --> 10:16.665
 I said don't say anything!     

10:16.700 --> 10:18.166
     Nobody listens to me.      

10:18.201 --> 10:18.717
         I listen to...         

10:18.752 --> 10:21.437
Shut up, shut up, shut up!      

10:21.471 --> 10:24.706
         Just stay away         
     and leave me alone!        

10:24.740 --> 10:26.942
I'm going to my room,           

10:26.976 --> 10:28.977
    wait for the angel of death.

10:35.569 --> 10:37.603
Oh, here's one                  
of my favorite paintings        

10:37.637 --> 10:39.471
of the Comuneros.               

10:39.506 --> 10:41.640
It depicts the peasant army     
struggling                      

10:41.675 --> 10:44.876
to push this cannon             
to the top of the hill.         

10:44.911 --> 10:47.213
Later, they found out           
they were on the wrong hill     

10:47.247 --> 10:49.348
and had fired                   
on their own village.           

10:49.382 --> 10:53.686
These people                    
had no luck.                    

10:55.171 --> 10:58.223
             That's fascinating,
             Dorothy.           

10:58.258 --> 11:00.426
         Isn't that             
         fascinating, Frasier?  

11:01.645 --> 11:03.012
         Oh, yes, yes.          

11:03.046 --> 11:07.016
You know, these stories make me 
 long to visit Paraguay...      

11:07.050 --> 11:09.551
         right now.             

11:12.305 --> 11:14.974
    ( <i>hooting and cheering</i> )    

11:15.675 --> 11:17.727
I hired you                     
as a temporary waitress.        

11:17.761 --> 11:19.862
What on earth were you doing    
with your blouse off?           

11:19.896 --> 11:21.330
                 Serving drinks.

11:21.365 --> 11:22.832
This is not a topless bar.      

11:22.866 --> 11:25.067
             What, I'm supposed 
             to get tips for    
             good service?      

11:25.101 --> 11:27.069
             Yes, dear, that's  
             the way we do      
             it around here.    

11:27.103 --> 11:28.337
Well, I'm sorry,                

11:28.372 --> 11:30.673
but I don't beauties            
like these under wraps.         

11:30.707 --> 11:32.140
             Out.               

11:32.175 --> 11:33.508
Out!                            

11:33.543 --> 11:35.878
 God, that is the fourth temp   

11:35.912 --> 11:37.380
waitress we've gone through.    

11:37.414 --> 11:38.547
        I hate this bar.        

11:38.582 --> 11:40.549
Excuse me, Miss,                
can we get some service?        

11:40.584 --> 11:42.017
                     Yes, sir.  

11:42.051 --> 11:43.352
                         WOMAN: 
                         Miss,  

11:43.387 --> 11:44.720
                this martini    
                is too dry.     

11:44.755 --> 11:46.889
Oh, I'm sorry.                  
I'll take care of that.         

11:46.923 --> 11:48.056
         I've had it.           

11:48.091 --> 11:49.492
 Isn't Carla ever coming back?  

11:49.526 --> 11:51.026
         I was not born         
     to be a waitress.          

11:51.060 --> 11:52.595
         I was born             
     to manage waitresses.      

11:52.629 --> 11:55.263
                    Oh, Miss?   
You'll get it                   
when I'm damn good and ready!   

11:57.867 --> 11:59.034
            Oh, God.            

11:59.068 --> 12:00.869
             Well, we tried     
             to cheer up Carla, 

12:00.903 --> 12:02.571
                but I don't     
                think it worked.

12:02.606 --> 12:04.473
 Yeah? How far did you get?     

12:04.507 --> 12:06.141
                    About a half
                    block away. 

12:06.176 --> 12:09.044
             She hit Mr. Clavin 
             with a rock.       

12:10.346 --> 12:12.181
Woody, uh, would you have       
a little look-see?              

12:12.215 --> 12:13.348
Is there a lump up there?       

12:13.383 --> 12:14.916
                Well, let's see.

12:14.951 --> 12:16.151
                No.             

12:16.186 --> 12:19.388
                Gee, Mr. Clavin,
                do you pluck    
                your eyebrows?  

12:19.422 --> 12:21.490
( <i>groans</i> )                      

12:22.825 --> 12:24.460
     We can't get along         
     without Carla here.        

12:24.494 --> 12:25.694
How can we get her back?        

12:25.728 --> 12:27.496
    Uh, well, I don't know,     
        but let's start         

12:27.530 --> 12:28.663
             at square one here.

12:28.698 --> 12:29.998
                 We know that,  
                 uh, she's upset

12:30.032 --> 12:31.567
             about having a     
             grandchild, right? 

12:31.601 --> 12:33.268
Another round, Sam?             

12:33.303 --> 12:34.370
                Coming right up.

12:34.404 --> 12:36.405
             Table 11, please.  

12:38.207 --> 12:39.541
Well, she was complaining       

12:39.576 --> 12:41.943
 that she'd missed out on all   
 that teenage stuff, you know?  

12:41.978 --> 12:43.345
Homecoming, proms, may...       

12:43.379 --> 12:44.814
 What-What if we do something   

12:44.848 --> 12:46.749
        to take her back        
     to her teen years?         

12:46.783 --> 12:47.883
     Like get her pregnant?     

12:47.917 --> 12:49.151
                         CLIFF: 
                         No.    

12:49.185 --> 12:51.186
        That's been done        
         to death.              

12:53.289 --> 12:54.890
W-What else did she say?        
What else?                      

12:54.924 --> 12:56.158
             Uh, let me think,  
             let me think.      

12:56.192 --> 12:57.826
            All right, something
            about a sleep over. 

12:57.861 --> 12:59.061
                 No, no, I know.
                 Slumber party. 

12:59.095 --> 13:00.062
            Yeah, slumber party.

13:00.096 --> 13:01.063
A slumber party?                
                    Right.      

13:01.097 --> 13:02.430
                Well, that's it.

13:02.465 --> 13:03.799
             Why don't we just  
             throw the woman    

13:03.833 --> 13:05.650
         a slumber party, and   
         that'll cheer her up.  

13:05.685 --> 13:07.519
Recreating a ritual             
of youth is often               

13:07.553 --> 13:08.821
just the thing                  
to get someone                  

13:08.855 --> 13:11.356
out of depression centered      
on a fear of aging.             

13:11.390 --> 13:13.358
I find it also helps            
to listen to heavy doses        

13:13.392 --> 13:15.894
of Credence Clearwater Revival. 

13:17.463 --> 13:18.764
                        REBECCA:
                        Great.  

13:18.798 --> 13:20.165
             I'm gonna do that. 
             SAM:               
             All right.         

13:20.200 --> 13:21.233
             REBECCA:           
             Just one question. 

13:21.267 --> 13:22.835
             What-what do you do
             at a slumber party?

13:22.869 --> 13:25.037
                Well, the phrase
                "slumber party" 

13:25.071 --> 13:27.072
                would imply     
                that one sleeps,

13:27.107 --> 13:30.342
     but somehow I sense        
     that's meant to be ironic. 

13:31.912 --> 13:34.212
         Terrific. We're really 
         on a roll here.        

13:34.247 --> 13:35.647
I have a patient of that age.   

13:35.682 --> 13:37.349
I suppose                       
I could do some research        

13:37.384 --> 13:38.751
             and help you put   
             something together.

13:38.885 --> 13:39.835
             REBECCA:           
             Thank you, Lilith. 

13:39.869 --> 13:41.069
                I would really  
                appreciate that.

13:41.104 --> 13:42.437
                    LILITH:     
                    Certainly.  
Say, Rebecca,                   

13:42.471 --> 13:43.104
if you're in need               

13:43.139 --> 13:44.356
of some extra guests,           

13:44.391 --> 13:45.757
I know a couple                 
of fun-loving gals              

13:45.792 --> 13:47.393
            who could really use
            a night on the town 

13:47.427 --> 13:48.427
                 away from      
                 boring old me. 

13:48.461 --> 13:50.596
And, uh,                        

13:50.630 --> 13:51.864
                 Lilith, you've 
                 always told me 

13:51.898 --> 13:53.799
         that you found Carla   
         an interesting, uh...  

13:53.833 --> 13:55.467
                 psychological  
                 case study.    

13:55.502 --> 13:56.769
Won't you be lonely?            

13:56.803 --> 13:57.703
FRASIER:                        
Well, it'll give me             

13:57.737 --> 13:59.754
            a chance to be alone
            with Dorothy's books

13:59.789 --> 14:01.990
             and a roaring fire.

14:05.912 --> 14:07.946
                Well, what do   
                you say, Lilith?

14:07.981 --> 14:10.615
 ¶ Big wheel keep on turning    

14:10.650 --> 14:12.885
 ¶ Proud Mary keep on burning   

14:12.919 --> 14:14.719
¶ Rolling                       
        ¶ Rolling               

14:14.754 --> 14:16.155
    ¶ Rolling                   
            ¶ Rolling           

14:16.189 --> 14:18.891
             BOTH:              
 ¶ Rolling on the river...      

14:18.925 --> 14:22.527
You know, you don't often get   
to see them loosen up like this.

14:33.539 --> 14:35.507
( <i>whispering</i> ):                 
Come on in, the coast is clear. 

14:35.541 --> 14:36.775
            Hi, Eddie.          
Hey, how you doing?             

14:36.809 --> 14:38.510
    Good.                       
Hi, uh...                       
how are you?                    

14:38.544 --> 14:39.811
             There you go.      
                     Thank you  
                     so much.   

14:39.845 --> 14:41.846
                     Sure, sure.

14:41.881 --> 14:43.482
            All right, I'm gonna
            put on the 45s.     

14:44.450 --> 14:45.484
                 Where's Carla? 

14:45.518 --> 14:46.818
She's in the back room knitting.

14:46.852 --> 14:48.687
             Oh, that's a sign  
             she's perking up.  

14:48.721 --> 14:49.854
I don't think so.               

14:49.889 --> 14:51.890
It's her death shroud.          

14:53.859 --> 14:55.460
        Oh, no.                 

14:55.495 --> 14:58.397
I forgot the marshmallows       
for the hot chocolate.          

14:58.431 --> 15:01.300
     That's okay, we'll use     
     the ones for the s'mores.  

15:01.334 --> 15:03.802
     Then what will we use      
        for the s'mores?        

15:03.836 --> 15:05.337
     Why don't we just skip     
         the s'mores?           

15:05.371 --> 15:07.673
You've been trying to get rid of
the s'mores since we've started.

15:07.707 --> 15:08.840
         No, I haven't.         

15:08.874 --> 15:10.309
You most certainly have...      

15:10.343 --> 15:11.343
    Shh! Shh!                   

15:13.212 --> 15:14.479
         Go get Carla.          

15:14.514 --> 15:15.647
                Hey, Carla,     

15:15.682 --> 15:17.081
                could you come  
                out here for    
                a second?       

15:17.116 --> 15:18.817
                         CARLA: 
                         No!    

15:18.851 --> 15:21.386
 I'd like to discuss something  
 about your, uh, grave site.    

15:21.421 --> 15:22.988
                 CARLA:         
                 Be right there.

15:25.008 --> 15:27.175
         ( <i>door opens</i> )         

15:31.697 --> 15:32.448
        Now!                    

15:32.482 --> 15:34.867
             ALL:               
         Surprise!              

15:34.901 --> 15:36.068
         What the hell          

15:36.102 --> 15:37.870
     are you doing here?        

15:37.904 --> 15:40.039
             ALL:               
 We're having a slumber party!  

15:40.073 --> 15:41.790
LILITH:                         
That's right, Carla.            

15:41.825 --> 15:43.742
Hold on to your hat;            
the gals are here.              

15:43.776 --> 15:45.610
        Eddie, get the gun.     

15:45.645 --> 15:46.678
Now, Carla,                     

15:46.713 --> 15:47.846
we know you're down,            

15:47.880 --> 15:50.181
but being alone is no way       
to deal with depression.        

15:50.216 --> 15:51.983
You need your friends           
around you.                     

15:52.017 --> 15:53.385
                    Good idea.  

15:53.419 --> 15:54.720
         Who the hell are you?  

15:56.756 --> 15:57.922
        Dorothy.                

15:57.957 --> 16:00.091
Dorothy Greenberg.              

16:00.125 --> 16:02.193
             Well, listen,      
             Dorothy, Dorothy,  

16:02.228 --> 16:03.462
            get the hell        
            out of here,        

16:03.496 --> 16:04.963
             and take all       
             this crap with you.

16:04.997 --> 16:06.331
        Now, come on, Carla.    
                    Go, go, go! 

16:06.366 --> 16:07.466
                Come on.        

16:07.500 --> 16:08.633
         Why'd you let them in? 

16:08.668 --> 16:09.951
Because for the last four days  

16:09.986 --> 16:11.920
you've been sitting around      
moping and whining              

16:11.954 --> 16:13.054
and scaring the kids.           

16:13.089 --> 16:14.189
I mean, for God's sake,         

16:14.223 --> 16:15.723
you haven't                     
yelled at them once.            

16:15.758 --> 16:19.427
Don't you think children        
notice those things?            

16:19.461 --> 16:21.429
         You're right,          
         I'm not a fit mother.  

16:21.463 --> 16:22.831
         I'll leave immediately.

16:22.865 --> 16:23.965
No, no, no.                     

16:24.000 --> 16:25.366
Come on, Carla, look.           

16:25.401 --> 16:27.869
     Look, if you're not gonna  
     do this for yourself,      

16:27.904 --> 16:29.070
         will you do it for me? 

16:29.105 --> 16:32.240
         I can't live with you  
         like this anymore.     

16:32.275 --> 16:34.575
         Look, sweetie, gi-give 
         it a chance, would you?

16:34.610 --> 16:35.911
     Come on, give it an hour.  

16:35.945 --> 16:37.078
( <i>sighs</i> )                       

16:37.113 --> 16:38.546
Look, if I do this,             

16:38.580 --> 16:40.615
would you and the Supremes      

16:40.649 --> 16:42.617
                 promise to     
                 leave me alone,

16:42.651 --> 16:44.219
get off my back?                

16:44.253 --> 16:45.386
                We promise.     

16:45.421 --> 16:47.923
All right,                      
let's get the thing over with.  

16:47.957 --> 16:50.792
Let the slumber party begin.    

16:52.962 --> 16:54.612
     I'm going to take off      
     for about an hour,         

16:54.647 --> 16:56.748
then I'm gonna come back        
and help you clean up           

16:56.782 --> 16:58.516
after you have                  
all your wacky gal fun.         

16:58.551 --> 17:00.252
        Bring body bags.        

17:05.491 --> 17:07.125
             Well, Lilith,      
             you have the list. 

17:07.159 --> 17:08.259
             Where do we start? 

17:08.294 --> 17:09.528
( <i>paper rustling</i> )              

17:09.561 --> 17:11.229
         All right, let's see.  

17:11.262 --> 17:12.830
 All right, so on the list      

17:12.865 --> 17:15.199
     we have to do, uh,         
     each other's hair.         

17:15.233 --> 17:18.002
        Then we talk about boys.

17:18.037 --> 17:19.905
        Ooh, tell scary stories.

17:19.939 --> 17:21.239
            Have a pillow fight,

17:21.272 --> 17:23.174
             and then for       
             the grand finale,  

17:23.208 --> 17:24.742
         assorted madcap pranks.

17:24.777 --> 17:28.112
 What kind of pranks?           

17:28.146 --> 17:29.648
According to my patient,        

17:29.682 --> 17:32.017
when the first person           
falls asleep,                   

17:32.051 --> 17:35.154
the others take her underwear,  
dip it in water                 

17:35.188 --> 17:37.956
and then put it                 
in the icebox for an hour       

17:37.990 --> 17:39.324
to freeze it solid.             

17:40.360 --> 17:43.295
     Or they could let you      
    wear it for ten minutes.    

17:46.116 --> 17:47.365
             Why don't we just  

17:47.399 --> 17:50.202
                 move to the    
                 pillow fight?  

17:53.172 --> 17:54.306
         Do that again,         

17:54.340 --> 17:57.008
         and they'll be         
     tracing you in chalk.      

17:57.043 --> 17:59.677
                 Uh-oh, Carla.  

17:59.712 --> 18:03.599
         I saw the corners of   
         your mouth twitching.  

18:03.633 --> 18:05.367
         Are there little elves 

18:05.401 --> 18:06.702
                pulling on them?

18:06.736 --> 18:08.937
                         Up. Up.

18:08.971 --> 18:10.338
         Oh, here they go again.

18:10.440 --> 18:12.124
                 Are you trying 
                 not to smile?  

18:12.158 --> 18:15.027
     No, I'm getting ready      
        to spit on you.         

18:21.083 --> 18:23.101
             CLIFF:             
Yep, in a little under an hour, 

18:23.135 --> 18:24.736
 Hector "The Hammer" Rodriguez  

18:24.770 --> 18:27.239
        will be nailing         
 Julio "The Hasbeen" Rodriguez  

18:27.273 --> 18:28.940
 into the canvas on our new TV. 

18:28.974 --> 18:30.008
Cliffie, in your dreams.        

18:30.042 --> 18:32.010
I say "The Hammer"              
goes down in five rounds.       

18:32.044 --> 18:33.312
                You're on.      

18:33.346 --> 18:34.413
         I say three.           
                        Two.    

18:34.447 --> 18:35.647
                All right.      
Get some                        
money up here.                  

18:35.682 --> 18:37.015
            We don't even       
            have a manual.      

18:37.049 --> 18:38.883
        How are you gonna       
        hook that thing up?     

18:38.918 --> 18:39.951
                     WOODY:     
                     Easy, Sam. 

18:39.985 --> 18:41.903
         They included          
     a special videotape        

18:41.937 --> 18:44.439
        showing exactly         
 how to hook everything up.     

18:44.474 --> 18:47.041
     So all we have to do       
     is hook everything up,     

18:47.076 --> 18:48.176
        watch the tape,         

18:48.211 --> 18:50.412
     and then we'll know        
     exactly what to do.        

18:53.433 --> 18:54.533
                 Okay, how long 

18:54.567 --> 18:57.302
         before Woody spots the 
         flaw in his reasoning? 

18:57.336 --> 19:00.072
                 I say, uh,     
                 eight minutes. 
            Give me three.      

19:00.106 --> 19:02.140
        Okay, I say five.       
I say two.                      

19:04.243 --> 19:05.677
Yeah, I'm in, I'm in.           
        ( <i>phone rings</i> )         

19:05.711 --> 19:06.911
Wait a minute, wait a minute.   

19:06.946 --> 19:08.113
There you go.                   
I'm in for ten.                 

19:08.147 --> 19:09.381
        Cheers.                 

19:09.415 --> 19:10.548
Sam, we're over here at Carla's,

19:10.582 --> 19:12.050
    but things aren't going     
         very well.             

19:12.084 --> 19:12.901
     I thought that maybe       

19:12.935 --> 19:14.852
    you guys could come over    
     and crash the party.       

19:14.887 --> 19:17.438
     You know, something        
to shake things up a little bit?

19:17.473 --> 19:18.707
         I'm desperate.         

19:18.741 --> 19:19.958
         Oh, really?            

19:19.992 --> 19:22.461
 I bet you're kind of sexy      
 when you're desperate, huh?    

19:23.946 --> 19:24.679
     Breathing heavily?         

19:24.714 --> 19:25.880
                        Sam.    

19:25.915 --> 19:27.031
     Is your chest heaving?     

19:27.066 --> 19:28.232
                    Sam, please.

19:28.267 --> 19:29.768
 Is your nightgown clinging     

19:29.802 --> 19:31.536
 to your sweat-soaked body?     

19:32.538 --> 19:34.089
                        Yes.    

19:34.123 --> 19:35.907
     We're on our way.          

19:37.709 --> 19:38.676
                 Hang on here.  

19:38.711 --> 19:40.629
         How can I hook this up 
         to watch the tape      

19:40.663 --> 19:42.464
             if I don't know    
             how to hook it up? 

19:42.498 --> 19:44.032
            Uh, two minutes.    
No.                             

19:44.067 --> 19:44.966
         Who had two?           

19:45.084 --> 19:46.818
            ( <i>groaning</i> )        

19:49.722 --> 19:51.073
     Listen, guys, uh,          
     that was Rebecca.          

19:51.107 --> 19:52.440
 Uh, slumber party's gone sour. 

19:52.474 --> 19:53.541
     Let's go help her out.     

19:53.576 --> 19:55.143
    Wait, wait, Sam,            
    what about the fight?       

19:55.178 --> 19:56.244
Oh, come on.                    

19:56.279 --> 19:58.346
You think Woody's gonna be      
able to fix that?               

19:58.381 --> 20:00.515
No one but Carla                
can hook up a TV around here.   

20:00.550 --> 20:02.784
So we'll go cheer her up        
and bring her back.             

20:02.818 --> 20:04.235
             Don't be so harsh  
             on the kid, Sam.   

20:04.270 --> 20:05.470
     Have a little faith here.  

20:05.505 --> 20:06.638
         Wait a minute.         

20:06.673 --> 20:08.507
 What are all these wires?      

20:10.343 --> 20:11.876
                 Party's gone   
                 sour, you say. 

20:13.879 --> 20:16.265
     ( <i>soft rock playing</i> )      

20:27.510 --> 20:29.277
     Want another s'more?       

20:29.311 --> 20:31.079
                 Not sweet      
                 enough for me. 

20:31.113 --> 20:34.082
         I think I'll just      
         have a bowl of syrup.  

20:34.116 --> 20:36.117
REBECCA:                        
Look, Carla.                    

20:36.151 --> 20:38.152
         Lilith's hair          
     is coming out nice.        

20:38.187 --> 20:40.288
        Yeah, in clumps.        

20:42.324 --> 20:44.659
     Carla, do you want me      
     to fix your hair, too?     

20:44.694 --> 20:45.727
What do you say?                

20:45.762 --> 20:48.062
                 I say your hour
                 is almost over.

20:48.097 --> 20:49.531
    Right.                      

20:49.565 --> 20:52.734
            Um, let's see what's
            next on the list?   

20:52.769 --> 20:54.135
        Ooh, good!              

20:54.169 --> 20:56.438
We get to tell scary stories.   

20:56.472 --> 20:58.373
You want to hear a scary story? 

20:58.408 --> 21:00.174
 I'll tell you a scary story.   

21:00.209 --> 21:02.878
 My life, that's a scary story. 

21:02.912 --> 21:04.762
             Wonderful, Carla!  

21:04.797 --> 21:06.698
             Okay, who's next?  

21:08.301 --> 21:10.551
     ( <i>doorbell rings</i> )         

21:10.586 --> 21:11.987
Oh, I hope it's not some boys   

21:12.021 --> 21:13.721
        trying to crash         
     our slumber party.         

21:15.324 --> 21:16.992
                         What?! 

21:17.026 --> 21:18.293
Hi, listen.                     
                         What?! 

21:18.327 --> 21:19.727
I know, I know you              
don't want to see me.           

21:19.762 --> 21:20.829
But I'll bet you want to see    

21:20.863 --> 21:21.897
the Four Swell Guys.            

21:21.931 --> 21:23.131
            We're going to      
            be bringing you     

21:23.166 --> 21:24.800
         memories of your       
         swinging teenage years.

21:24.834 --> 21:26.968
             ( <i>deepens voice</i> ): 
             Do you remember    
             this, Carla?       

21:27.003 --> 21:29.554
     ¶ Duke, Duke, Duke,        
         Duke of Earl ¶         

21:29.588 --> 21:31.056
 ¶ Duke, Duke, Duke of Earl     

21:31.090 --> 21:33.725
         ¶ Duke, Duke,          
         Duke of Earl ¶         

21:33.759 --> 21:35.560
¶ Duke, Duke, Duke of Earl      

21:35.594 --> 21:37.795
         ¶ As I walked          
     through this world ¶       

21:37.830 --> 21:40.565
 ¶ <i>Duke, Duke, Duke of Earl</i> ¶   

21:40.599 --> 21:42.634
¶ Nothing can stop...           
            Shut up!            

21:42.668 --> 21:43.968
     ¶ Duke, Duke...            

21:44.003 --> 21:46.071
         Why do you all         
     keep coming over here?     

21:46.105 --> 21:47.972
 We're trying to cheer you up.  

21:48.007 --> 21:49.207
         Well, stop it!         

21:50.343 --> 21:51.593
     You can't cheer me up.     

21:51.627 --> 21:52.928
             Why do people think

21:52.962 --> 21:54.930
                they always have
                to rush over    

21:54.964 --> 21:56.698
 a-and talk somebody out of it  

21:56.732 --> 21:58.399
 when they're feeling lousy?    

21:58.434 --> 22:00.251
                 ( <i>Carla sighs</i> )

22:00.285 --> 22:01.903
 Look, this grandmother thing   

22:01.937 --> 22:04.372
     is just something          
    I have to work through,     

22:04.406 --> 22:05.573
     and I will in time.        

22:08.177 --> 22:10.511
        There's nothing         
 any of you guys could do.      

22:10.546 --> 22:13.481
Unless you can make me 15 again.

22:14.850 --> 22:16.051
         Can any of you         

22:16.085 --> 22:17.719
     make me 15 again?          

22:20.422 --> 22:22.741
         Well, can you?         

22:25.944 --> 22:28.279
     Look, if you really        
        cared about me,         

22:28.314 --> 22:30.982
     you would just...          
     get out of my house        

22:31.016 --> 22:34.185
 and do what I asked you to     
        a long time ago.        

22:34.219 --> 22:38.222
 Just... just leave me alone.   

22:41.127 --> 22:42.143
You mean you really             

22:42.178 --> 22:43.595
want to be left alone?          

22:47.666 --> 22:49.201
        Let's go, guys.         
        Come on.                

22:49.235 --> 22:50.802
                     Now what?  

22:50.836 --> 22:51.903
     The party was stupid.      

22:51.937 --> 22:54.172
DOROTHY:                        
This was not a stupid party.    

22:54.207 --> 22:55.607
 Oh, well, I stand corrected.   

22:55.641 --> 22:57.542
    It was the social event     
         of the season.         

22:58.611 --> 22:59.777
    Shut up.                    

22:59.812 --> 23:02.080
         Oh, yeah? You want     
         a punch in the mouth?  

23:04.783 --> 23:06.818
 You're gonna be all right?     

23:06.852 --> 23:08.035
             Yeah.              

23:08.070 --> 23:10.505
         I appreciate           
 what you tried to do, Sam.     

23:10.539 --> 23:12.757
                 I'll be okay,  
                 you know?      

23:12.791 --> 23:15.726
     You know, something        
     always comes along,        

23:15.761 --> 23:18.163
     some little something,     

23:18.197 --> 23:19.797
 makes everything work out.     

23:20.966 --> 23:21.967
 But I got to find it myself.   

23:22.001 --> 23:23.101
    You can't do it for me.     

23:23.135 --> 23:24.735
         All right.             

23:26.255 --> 23:28.923
     You know my number.        

23:28.958 --> 23:31.776
( <i>door closes</i> )                 

23:31.810 --> 23:33.361
( <i>latch turns</i> )                 

23:34.297 --> 23:35.514
     Sorry, Carla, I, uh...     

23:35.548 --> 23:37.682
( <i>clears throat</i> )               

23:37.717 --> 23:39.367
 ... just forgot my jacket.     

23:39.401 --> 23:41.068
( <i>ripping sound</i> )               

